tegrating civic engagement into the work of scholars, creating a civic engagement minor at CSU Dominguez Hills, integrating community organizing practices within an LA school district, and building a regional organizing network among civically engaged higher education institutions.As the case studies authored by Maria Avila and her collaborators show, these projects succeeded because they took place in collaborative spaces where participants were part of designing the purpose, goals, and specific actions to create culture change. Building Collective Leadership for Culture Change is a vital inquiry into the possibilities of collective interpretation among researchers and participants of their accomplishments.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mai 2023) 0aCommunity organization. 0aCommunity-based research. 0aSocial change. 0aSocial participation. 4aSOCIOLOGY & SOCIAL SCIENCE. 4aURBAN STUDIES. 7aEDUCATION / Inclusive Education.2bisacsh  acivic engagement, culture change in higher education, collaborative learning, community organizing, collective leadership, academic silos, relational community.1 aAman Rivera, Aixle, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAvila, Maria, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCastillo, Celestina, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDeng, Xuefei, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKnoerr, Alan P., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLópez-Chang, Ray, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMoreno, Alexis, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aOrtega, Enrique, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPerez, Joanna B, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.go